Dear Hair!

We’ve been through so much — I can admit that haven’t always been the kindest. As a kid, braids and extensions kept things easy to manage, but as a young adult, I wanted to explore your natural texture. Over the years, I’m always learning how to take care of you. I feel affirmed in the style I’ve settled on, and I’m proud of the tight, sort of chaotic curls I have. My short hair is one of my favourite features — it just feels like me. 

Thank you for teaching me more about myself — I hope I can treat you as well as you continue to treat me.

Xo,
Lydia

It may not be realistic for all brands to carry extended sizing, but when brands pick and choose what to offer in plus sizes, it make a distinct statement. 

Some 66 per cent of American women wear size 14 or larger, and yet the apparel industry produces between 2%-12% of clothing in extended sizing. Despite being in the majority, fat customers don’t deserve the same options as their thin counterparts. Bigger folks can’t access the same creativity and expression as thin folks. Plus people are not as stylish as thin folks. Plus size are being included but *clearly* not equal. Wouldn’t it be amazing to see this mentality shift? 

What do you think could be improved from brands that DO carry extended & plus sizing?

Personal style is a playground to share many messages; for queer folks clothing is often a starting point of experimenting with their identity. Whether it’s seeing a side of yourself for the first time, or gender affirming garments that fit the real you — the power of clothing for the queer community should not be underestimated. On my gender journeys particularly, I get a lot of gender euphoria from wearing clothing that suits the facets of my non-binary identity. 

I appreciate that @PoshmarkCanada gave some space for me to chat about my style and queerness as it’s Pride Month. I feel an extreme privilege to live and work somewhere that my identity can (generally) be expressed freely. Hoping for a future where that can be true for all of us in the community. 

Happy pride to my queer siblings — I see you, I love you and I hope that you get moments to celebrate joy with queer community this month!

#PoshPartner #PoshmarkCanada #LGBTQ+ #Pride

I’ve ruminated, pondered and circled the question of my gender identity in direct confrontation with my style identity.

I’m known to be immediately drawn to many floofy, confectionary, extra, bold and decidedly femme coded articles of clothing. And when I found my way to my non-binary identity — I really struggled to validate my own gender feelings with how I dress. The transphobia of “not fitting” the androgynous stereotype really f cked with my head. 

Recently I had a chance to navigate my own findings, as well as how the fashion industry approaches the concept of gender inclusive clothing for @fashioncanada, in print and online!

I want to disclaim that these are the opinions of one gender diverse person — I wouldn’t claim to speak for all non-binary/trans/gender diverse folks. But it would mean a lot to me if you took a moment to read (linked in bio); I think all of us benefit from a vision of personal style that is not encased in prescriptive categories and instead, embraces the genderful nature of existing.

YO, DOES THAT SHOW UP ON YOU? | Episode 3! Trying out rainbow eyeshadow from the drugstore. Quo Beauty’s Love Is Love Eyeshadow Palette is a dry/wet use palette — and my findings were interesting! The colours changed drastically when wet. 

For folks with deep skintones, I think this is only usable as a wet eyeshadow. Use a setting spray or face mist to wet the brush to apply — I used @af94’s 5 in 1 spray. I would not recommend dry use; lots of fallout and not a ton of colour payoff. 

Happy final day of Pride Month — you know I had to do something on theme!

Ok! So! We are so excited to share fit notes on our clothes swap because online shopping is SO HARD and sometimes you just want to try something on. We are typically similar sizes despite our proportions being a little different, so this was such a fun exercise to see how different styles and brands fit us. 

What Lo Wants | Dress (Marielle) 
The 3X is definitely the right size for my chest, and I was surprised by how much I loved this print. It feels delightfully etheral, and the fabric is so light for Summer.

Shelter | Silk Slip (Lydia)
The size is great at my hips — I look forward to the final version with adjustable straps because my chest does NOT fill it out where it sits currently. A silk slip dress feels very main character.

Reformation | Shorts (Marielle)
Ok, so I took these home with me because the fit just doesn't work for Lydia and was one of the only pieces that didn't fit both of us. It definitely works well for a large hip to waist ratio and I loved the length of these.

WRAY | Shorts (Lydia)
I have this style of Wray short in one size down. Now I know the 4X is my size in these, super comfortable!

What Lo Wants | Cobalt Set (Marielle)
This set fits like an actual dream. I don't have a closet gap for it right now, but oh this is such a cute look. This was my first time trying WLW and I am so impressed with the quality and fit, would absolutely reccomend.

WRAY | Cargos (Lydia)
By the measurements, I wasn’t sure what size I’d take in this piece, so I was happy to try Marielle’s pair. They fit like a dream, and the fabric feels sturdy but not constructive. Love this style.

sometimes we k.i.s.s. (keep it simple, silly)
